{
  "step": 2,
  "title": "The Dopamine Loop",
  "startFrame": 1029,
  "endFrame": 3216,
  "componentPath": "src/visuals/Generated_TheDopamineLoop.tsx",
  "transcriptSegment": "Here's what's actually going on inside your head. Every time you hit a coding problem and immediately reach for chat G P T, your brain releases a small hit of dopamine. Not when you solve the problem, but the moment you decide to ask for help. It's the same neurochemical pathway that makes slot machines so addictive. The anticipation of the reward, not the reward itself.\n\nMeta's internal research team found that their own engineers were using A I assistance for an average of forty-seven coding tasks per day. That's once every ten minutes during an eight-hour workday. Each query triggers that same dopamine hit, training your brain to crave the next fix. You've essentially turned your development workflow into a behavioral addiction loop.\n\nThe problem gets worse because your tolerance builds over time. What started as using A I for complex algorithms now extends to basic syntax. Developers at Google reported asking chat G P T how to write for loops in languages they've been using for years. Your brain stops bothering to remember information it knows will be instantly available. It's like having a calculator for addition permanently attached to your hand.",
